methodology.workflowName: DRAGEN TruSight Oncology 500 Analysis Software v2.5.2 (with HRD)
methodology.assayDescription:
[DRAFT METHODOLOGY IS PROVIDED BASED ON GENERIC DOCUMENTATION FOR TWO OR MORE SEPARATE PRODUCTS. USERS NEED TO UPDATE THE METHODOLOGY AND GENE LISTS AS RELEVANT TO THEIR TEST]

The test was performed using the Illumina TruSight Oncology 500 HRD targeted enrichment sequencing assay including a DNA based panel covering 523 genes and an RNA based panel covering 55 genes. Single nucleotide variants (SNVs), insertions, deletions, copy number variants (CNV), exon-level CNVs, multinucleotide variants (MNVs), tumor mutational burden (TMB), microsatellite instability (MSI), and genomic Instability Score (GIS) were detected from DNA. Fusions and splice variants were detected from RNA.

Variant calling was performed by DRAGEN TruSight Oncology 500 Analysis Software against human genome build GRCh37.

Tumor mutational burden (TMB) was calculated as a number of mutations per megabase (mut/Mb) of the panel. Microsatellite instability (MSI) status was determined through interrogating 130 MSI marker sites and calculating the percentage of unstable sites.

To detect Genomic Instability Score (GIS), TruSight Oncology 500 HRD included ~25K genome-wide probes designed to assess for 3 genomic scars (loss of heterozygosity (LOH), telomeric-allelic imbalance (TAI), and large-scale state transitions (LST)) across a broad range of ethnicities. Myriad Genetics GIS algorithm was used to calculate the genomic scars and the resultant GIS.

Identified variants were annotated using Illumina Connected Annotations and a set of sources including JAX Clinical Knowledgebase (JAX-CKB), OncoKB, COSMIC, ClinVar, CancerHotspots, gnomAD, and others. Variants were prioritized and interpreted based on information from drug labels, clinical practice guidelines, publicly available databases, and peer-reviewed literature. Variants were classified using the AMP/ASCO/CAP guidelines on interpretation of sequence variants in cancer (Li et al., 2017) into four tiers: variants of strong clinical significance (Tier I), potential clinical significance (Tier II), unknown clinical significance (Tier III) and benign or likely benign variants (Tier IV).

reportLabels.gbVusAvailable: Variants of uncertain significance are detected and listed at the end of the report.
reportLabels.title: Title
reportLabels.smallVariantsDescription: Small variants (insertions, deletions, single nucleotide variants [SNV], and multiple nucleotide variants [MNV]) are detected from DNA.
reportLabels.copyNumberVariantsDescription: Copy number variants are detected from DNA and reflect a gain in the number of copies of a gene.
reportLabels.geneFusionsDescription: Gene fusions are detected from RNA and occur when portions of two genes are translated together into a novel RNA product.
reportLabels.spliceVariantsDescription: Splice variants are detected from RNA and are represented by two breakpoints, the associated gene, and affected exon(s) in that gene, as applicable.
reportLabels.tumorMutationalBurdenDescription: A measurement of the number of somatic mutations carried by tumor cells per megabase in the coding region.
reportLabels.microSatelliteDescription: Microsatellite instability is based on an assessment of the fraction of genomic sites found to be unstable (shown as a percentage).
reportLabels.systemVersionSuffix: For Research Use Only. Not for use in diagnostic procedures.
